  relationshipStyle: "Devoted, Sensory, Quietly Intense",
  relationshipPreview:
    "You love through presence, not performance. When you care about someone, they become the focus of your extraordinary attention — you remember what they wore, how their voice changed when they talked about their mother, the song that was playing when you first met. Your love language is shared experience: a walk, a meal cooked together, sitting in comfortable silence while the light changes. The tension is that the depth of your attachment may be invisible to partners who need words, and your difficulty expressing it verbally can be mistaken for not feeling it at all.",

  relationshipDeepDive:
    "Your relationship style has a specific architecture: deep internal attachment expressed through sensory experience and physical presence rather than verbal declaration. Understanding this architecture — and the ways it both serves and limits your connections — is essential for building relationships that actually reach you.\n\n**The Attraction Phase**\n\nYou fall for people the way you fall for anything — through direct experience rather than abstract evaluation. Something about them registers in your body before your mind catches up: the way they move, the quality of their laugh, the specific energy they bring into a room. Your lead function then runs a rapid values-check — is this person genuine? Is there substance beneath the surface? — and if they pass, you're drawn in with an intensity that would surprise anyone who sees only your quiet exterior.\n\nThe early phase of a Trailblazer's attraction is subtle and easily missed. You don't pursue aggressively. You gravitate — showing up where they are, offering small gestures that carry enormous internal significance, creating opportunities for shared sensory experience. A partner who's looking for obvious signals may not realize they're being chosen. A partner who's attuned to subtlety will recognize that your steady, quiet presence is the loudest declaration you know how to make.\n\n**The Deepening**\n\nAs the relationship deepens, your partner gains access to your inner world — slowly, in increments, as trust is earned. This isn't a conscious withholding strategy. Your lead function simply doesn't open to people who haven't demonstrated that they'll handle what's inside with care. Each act of trustworthiness opens a door. Each violation closes one. The process is non-negotiable and largely non-verbal.\n\nWhat your partner discovers inside is often surprising: the quiet person they're dating contains a universe of feeling, conviction, aesthetic sensitivity, and moral passion that the external presentation doesn't hint at. The experience of being trusted with a Trailblazer's inner world is one of the most intimate experiences available in human connection — which is why the people who have been there tend to describe it as unlike any other relationship they've had.\n\n**Conflict Style**\n\nConflict is genuinely difficult for you — not because you can't handle it, but because your lead function processes disagreement as a potential values violation. When a partner criticizes something connected to your identity or values, your system doesn't register 'they disagree with me.' It registers 'they're rejecting who I am.' This makes conflict feel existential even when it's mundane.\n\nYour default conflict response is withdrawal: you pull inward, go quiet, and process. This can look like stonewalling to a partner who needs verbal engagement, but internally you're doing essential work — sorting what's genuinely important from what's just reactive, checking whether the criticism hit a real vulnerability or just triggered a defensive reflex. The processing can take hours or days, and rushing it produces worse outcomes than waiting.\n\nThe growth edge in conflict: learning to say 'I need time to process this, and I will come back to it' rather than simply disappearing. The first version respects both your processing style and your partner's need for reassurance. The second version leaves your partner in an anxious void that damages trust.\n\n**Physical Connection and Intimacy**\n\nPhysical intimacy is one of your primary emotional languages. Your secondary function gives you body awareness, sensory attunement, and a quality of physical presence that turns touch into communication. For you, physical connection isn't separate from emotional connection — it is emotional connection, expressed through the medium your cognitive stack handles most fluently.\n\nYou're attuned to nuance: the difference between a touch that's present and one that's performative, the shift in a partner's breathing that signals something unspoken, the way physical closeness creates a space where your lead function can communicate what your words can't carry. Partners who share your comfort with physical expression experience this as extraordinary intimacy. Partners who need verbal emotional processing may experience it as a substitute for the conversation they actually need.\n\n**What Makes Relationships Last**\n\nYour ideal partner sees your inner world without requiring you to narrate it constantly. They read your gestures, respect your silences, and understand that when you cook them dinner or take them to a place you love, you're saying something that a thousand words couldn't improve. They bring enough verbal and organizational capacity to handle the external demands you find depleting, without making you feel inadequate for needing that support. And they never, ever ask you to be someone you're not — because your lead function will walk away from a relationship that requires sustained inauthenticity, no matter how much you love the person.\n\nThe deepest Trailblazer relationships have a quality that's hard to describe from the outside: a wordless understanding, a shared sensory world, a loyalty so complete it doesn't need to be stated. These relationships aren't built on excitement or intellectual stimulation (though both can be present). They're built on the rarest commodity your type has to offer: the full opening of your inner world to another person.",

